4. The Water Cycle
Low: 510L

Main Idea:
Water constantly moves through a cycle on Earth.

Supporting Details:
Evaporation of water into vapor
Condensation into clouds
Precipitation back to Earth's surface

Water cycle diagram
Water is always moving around our Earth in a cycle. The sun heats water in
oceans, lakes, and rivers. The heated water turns into water vapor and rises
into the sky. This is called evaporation. As water vapor cools, it forms clouds
through condensation. When clouds get too heavy, water falls back to Earth
as rain or snow. This is precipitation. The water then collects in oceans,
lakes, and rivers, and the cycle restarts.

Target Axes:
-ing (moving) -s (heats) -ed (heated) -es (rises) -tion (evaporation)
-s (cools) -tion (condensation) -s (falls) pre- (precipitation) re- (restarts)

5. Recycling Matters
Low: 520L

Main Idea:
Recycling helps the environment by reusing materials

Supporting Details:
Paper can be reused.
Plastic can be remade into new products.
Metal can be melted and reshaped.
Recycling reduces landll waste.
♲
Recycling bins and process
Recycling means using things again instead of throwing them away. Many
items we use daily can be recycled. Paper can be reused to make new
paper products. Plastic bottles can be remade into new bottles or clothing.
Metal cans are melted down and reshaped. Recycling helps keep our planet
cleaner and healthier. It also reduces the amount of trash in landfills. When
we recycle, we are being helpful to Earth.

Target Axes:
re- (recycling) -ing (throwing) re- (recycled) re- (reused) re- (remade)
-ing (clothing) -ed (melted) re- (reshaped) -er (cleaner) -er (healthier)
re- (reduces) -ful (helpful)

6. Plant Parts
Low: 530L

Main Idea:
Plants have dierent parts with specic functions

Supporting Details:
Roots collect water and nutrients.
Stems support and transport.
Leaves collect sunlight.
Flowers attract pollinators.

Plant diagram showing parts
Plants have many important parts that help them grow and live. The roots
grow underground and take in water and nutrients. The stem supports the
plant and carries water up to the leaves. Leaves are like solar panels that
collect sunlight to make food in a process called photosynthesis. Many
plants grow colorful flowers that attract pollinators like bees and
butterflies. After pollination, flowers turn into fruits or seeds that can grow
into new plants.

Target Axes:
-s (roots) under- (underground) -ent (nutrients) -s (supports)
-ful (colorful) -or (pollinator) -tion (pollination)


12. All About Teeth
585L

Main Idea:
Teeth have dierent parts and functions that require
proper care.

Supporting Details:
Teeth have protective enamel.
Dierent teeth have dierent jobs.
Teeth need regular brushing and ossing.
Dental checkups are important.

Teeth and dental care
Your teeth help you eat, speak, and smile. Each tooth has a hard outer
covering called enamel that protects it. Inside each tooth are nerves that
let you feel hot, cold, and pain. Different teeth have different jobs. Front
teeth help bite food, while back teeth grind and crush it. Keeping your teeth
healthy means brushing twice a day and flossing to remove food that gets
stuck between teeth. Regular checkups with a dentist also help keep your
smile bright.

Target Axes:
-ing (covering) in- (inside) -ing (keeping) -ing (brushing) -ing (ossing)
re- (remove) be- (between) -ar (regular) -ist (dentist)

14. Insect Bodies
Low: 595L

Main Idea:
Insects have specialized body parts with specic functions.

Supporting Details:
Three body sections: head, thorax, abdomen
Antennae for sensing
Compound eyes for vision
Six jointed legs
Many have wings
Grow through molting

Insect body parts labeled
Insects are the most successful animals on Earth, with more kinds than any
other animal group. All insects have three main body parts: the head,
thorax, and abdomen. On their heads, insects have two antennae for
sensing their surroundings. Most insects have compound eyes with many
tiny lenses that help them see in different directions at once. Insects have
six jointed legs attached to their thorax. Many insects have wings, which let
them fly. Insects grow by molting, shedding their hard exoskeleton as they
get bigger.


sur- (surroundings) com- (compound) -es (lenses) dif- (dierent)
-tion (direction) -ed (jointed) at- (attached) -ing (molting)
-ing (shedding) -er (bigger)
